==English==
===Etymology===
[[Middle French]] ''interposer,'' modification (influenced by ''poser'' to put, place) of Latin ''interponere'' ([[perfect]] stem ''interpos-''), from ''inter-'' + ''ponere'' to put, place

===Pronunciation===
*:Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-əʊz|-əʊz]]

===Verb===
'''To interpose'''  (''transitive'')
# To [[insert]] something (or oneself) between other things
# To [[interrupt]] a [[conversation]] by [[introducing]] a different [[subject]] or making a [[comment]]
'''To interpose'''  (''intransitive'')
# To be inserted between parts or things
# To [[intervene]] in a [[dispute]], or in a conversation

